We're in a container so that's not meaningful, but here's what you need to set up on your actual server:

Nginx — logrotate config

Create /etc/logrotate.d/nginx:

/var/log/nginx/*.log {
    daily
    rotate 30
    compress
    delaycompress
    missingok
    notifempty
    sharedscripts
    postrotate
        nginx -s reopen
    endscript
}

This keeps 30 days of logs, compresses old ones, and signals Nginx to reopen log files after rotation. Adjust rotate 30 to whatever retention period you put in your privacy policy.

Fastify — options

Fastify uses pino for logging by default. You have two good options:

Option A — pipe to a file and use logrotate (simplest)
bash

node server.js | pino-roll logs/app.log --frequency daily --limit 30

Then add a logrotate entry for your log path, similar to the Nginx one above.

Option B — use pino-roll programmatically (cleaner for a managed app)
js

import { createStream } from 'pino-roll'

const stream = await createStream('logs/app.log', {
  frequency: 'daily',
  limit: { count: 30 }
})

const app = fastify({ logger: { stream } })

Option B is tidier if you're running Fastify as a managed service (systemd, PM2, etc.).

